  "prompt": "Does four wheel drive consume more fuel than two wheel drive?",
  "response": "Yes, four-wheel drive (4WD) typically consumes more fuel than two-wheel drive (2WD) systems. The reasons for increased fuel consumption include:\n\n1. **Increased Weight**: 4WD systems often add weight to the vehicle due to additional components like transfer cases and driveshafts.\n\n2. **Increased Drivetrain Losses**: Power is distributed to all four wheels in 4WD, which results in more energy being lost in the drivetrain due to friction and mechanical resistance compared to 2WD, which only powers two wheels.\n\n3. **Rolling Resistance**: Vehicles in 4WD may experience more rolling resistance, particularly if they are designed for off-road capabilities or have larger tires suited for rugged terrain.\n\n4. **Aerodynamics**: Some 4WD vehicles are taller or have different body designs that may adversely affect aerodynamics compared to their 2WD counterparts.\n\n5. **Use of Engaged Systems**: If a 4WD system is full-time or if it\u2019s left in 4WD mode unnecessarily, it can lead to continual increased fuel consumption.\n\nIn situations where enhanced traction and stability are necessary, 4WD can be beneficial, but for everyday driving on paved roads, 2WD is generally more fuel-efficient.",
